WEBVTT

1
00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:24.810
(soft music)

2
00:02:22.130 --> 00:02:23.650
(honking)

3
00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:05.130
- Mado, look at this.

4
00:03:05.770 --> 00:03:07.170
Napoleon's.

5
00:03:07.290 --> 00:03:09.490
- Napoleon's?
- Mm-hmm. Napoleon's sabre.


6
00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:16.690
(in French):

7
00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:26.530
One of his sabres, I suppose.

8
00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:29.730
He must've had several of them.

9
00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:32.290
A man like Napoleon.

10
00:03:36.130 --> 00:03:37.730
(distant shouting)

11
00:03:40.370 --> 00:03:41.450
- Stephan?

12
00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:43.450
- Well?

13
00:03:44.130 --> 00:03:45.850
- Where did you get that sword?

14
00:03:47.050 --> 00:03:48.890
- From a Frenchman
named de Coligny.


15
00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:50.530
It belongs to his family.

16
00:03:52.170 --> 00:03:53.770
- Why are they selling it?

17
00:03:53.930 --> 00:03:56.330
- Because they need the money.
Everybody needs money.


18
00:03:56.450 --> 00:03:58.610
You know that. I know that.

19
00:04:00.730 --> 00:04:03.170
- But shouldn't he be taking it
to a museum?


20
00:04:03.290 --> 00:04:05.330
- He has to
do it on the sly.

21
00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:10.330
His uncle and his mother
don't want him to sell it.


22
00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:12.570
They would stop him
if they could.


23
00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:17.690
- He probably has no right to sell it
without his mother's consent.


24
00:04:18.690 --> 00:04:20.570
- His mother has nothing to say.

25
00:04:32.570 --> 00:04:34.330
- What you going to do with it?

26
00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:37.930
- I'm going to send it
to America.


27
00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:46.610
- But... that's illegal.

28
00:04:49.610 --> 00:04:52.570
- I saw a dress in the window
of Jean Veron's today.


29
00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:55.410
A sort of peach colour.

30
00:04:56.290 --> 00:04:58.210
You might call it apricot.

31
00:04:58.970 --> 00:05:00.530
It would suit you.

32
00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:02.010
- Really?

33
00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:03.930
- Oh, you don't think
I'm too pale?


34
00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:06.650
- Oh, you can't take
strong colours.


35
00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:09.130
- You're probably right.
- No, except black.


36
00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:10.850
I like you in black.
(laughing)


37
00:05:10.970 --> 00:05:13.330
- My black crepe de Chine,
that's chic, isn't it?


38
00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:15.410
- Mm. Makes you look
like a little nun.


39
00:05:15.530 --> 00:05:18.210
We should get you
a white-lace collar to go with it.


40
00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:31.850
(soft piano music playing)

41
00:06:16.890 --> 00:06:18.290
- Ah, there you are, Anna.

42
00:06:18.450 --> 00:06:21.410
- Lola's in the Select.
She'll be along in a minute.


43
00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:23.290
(indistinct chatter)

44
00:06:26.050 --> 00:06:28.810
I'm not in my assiette,
as the dear French say.


45
00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:31.290
- Now,
what are we going to have?


46
00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:33.370
- I've been trying to decide
who's worse: men or women.


47
00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:35.450
- Well, are we ready to order?

48
00:06:35.570 --> 00:06:39.090
- Women are worse. They'll kick your face
to bits if you let them.


49
00:06:39.210 --> 00:06:40.810
- Oh, darling,
don't be depressed.


50
00:06:40.970 --> 00:06:42.290
Have a fine.

51
00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:44.690
H.J., do call Lefranc.
We are ready to order.


52
00:06:44.850 --> 00:06:46.930
- Monsieur Lefranc.
(background chatter)


53
00:06:53.730 --> 00:06:56.690
- Did you see Cri-Cri
count me dead, H.J.?


54
00:06:56.810 --> 00:06:59.250
Considering she came to my party
last Saturday.


55
00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:02.290
- Oh, don't worry about her, my dear.
She's having her little hour.


56
00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:04.050
- Till her painter
throws her out.


57
00:07:04.170 --> 00:07:05.930
- She's a character.
She's a type.


58
00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:09.890
They have their little hour,
then we hear no more about them.


59
00:07:10.690 --> 00:07:11.930
- Mar ya.

60
00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:13.490
- Hello.

61
00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:17.050
- There's that little...
Zelli girl.


62
00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:23.210
- Couldn't you turn up tomorrow?
I wish you would.


63
00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:24.650
I'd like to talk to you.

64
00:07:24.770 --> 00:07:27.530
- I can't.
I have to meet my husband.


65
00:07:27.650 --> 00:07:30.490
- Where did she come from?
Does anybody know?


66
00:07:30.610 --> 00:07:32.730
- Somewhere rather vague
and exotic.


67
00:07:32.850 --> 00:07:34.850
Martinique? Could that be right?

68
00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:37.130
Anyway, her mother's
supposed to be a West Indian.


69
00:07:37.250 --> 00:07:38.370
- That means she's a Creole.

70
00:07:39.010 --> 00:07:40.210
- What is a Creole?

71
00:07:40.330 --> 00:07:43.490
- I thought it was a way of cooking chicken.
(nearby laughter)


72
00:07:45.010 --> 00:07:46.730
- Oh, you know the Heidlers,
do you?


73
00:07:46.850 --> 00:07:48.170
- Not very well.

74
00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:52.290
- Keep it that way.
- Why?


75
00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:57.290
If you have something to say,
I wish you'd say it.


76
00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:01.170
- I'm not too clear
about the whole thing, but...


77
00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:03.250
it seems there was a girl
who killed herself.


78
00:08:04.250 --> 00:08:06.050
Someone Heidler
had had an affair with.


79
00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:08.250
And then he had
some sort of breakdown,


80
00:08:08.370 --> 00:08:10.130
and his wife
had to take him away.


81
00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:12.770
To New York or somewhere.

82
00:08:12.890 --> 00:08:15.050
I believe Mrs. 
Heidler paints.

83
00:08:15.970 --> 00:08:18.450
It's pretty awful to think of
the hundreds of women round here


84
00:08:18.610 --> 00:08:20.010
painting away, isn't it?

85
00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:22.210
- She's a decorative
little person.


86
00:08:22.330 --> 00:08:24.570
You should get her
to sit for you, Lois.


87
00:08:24.690 --> 00:08:26.530
(background chatter)

88
00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:31.610
- What does he do?
- He's a very important man.


89
00:08:31.730 --> 00:08:33.410
He makes discoveries.

90
00:08:34.450 --> 00:08:35.610
He helps young people.

91
00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:37.890
He has flair.

92
00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:41.170
He also has money, of course.
And that helps.


93
00:08:41.290 --> 00:08:43.450
- ...working their fingers
to the bone for him,


94
00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:44.810
he doesn't have to do a thing;

95
00:08:44.970 --> 00:08:46.250
he doesn't have to pay
for servants.


96
00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:48.370
(French chatter)

97
00:08:58.090 --> 00:09:01.650
- I hate all that kind of thing.
Astral bodies and all the rest of it.


98
00:09:01.770 --> 00:09:05.210
- Astral bodies is theosophy.
- You've been neglecting us.


99
00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:08.170
You want to avoid English people
in Paris.


100
00:09:09.810 --> 00:09:12.410
H.J. and I most completely agree
with you.


101
00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:14.770
If you see only Anglo-Americans
in Paris,


102
00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:17.210
what's the use of being here
at all?


103
00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:19.570
Oh, your husband's French,
of course.


104
00:09:19.690 --> 00:09:21.090
- He's a Pole.

105
00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:24.570
- And he, uh...
- He's an art dealer.


106
00:09:25.090 --> 00:09:28.170
He acts between Frenchmen
who want to sell and foreigners.


107
00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:30.650
It's usually foreigners
who want to buy.


108
00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:33.730
- And what do the Frenchmen
want to sell?


109
00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:37.250
- Pictures, fur coats...

110
00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:39.930
Madame Dubarry's prie-dieu.

111
00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:41.130
Anything.

112
00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:44.050
-H.J.and I
have quite made up our minds


113
00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:46.050
that eating is the greatest
pleasure in life.


114
00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:47.810
Haven't we, H.J.?

115
00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:49.610
Well, I mean, it is, isn't it?

116
00:09:49.730 --> 00:09:51.810
It's one of the few pleasures
that never let you down.


117
00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:54.490
- Oh, the music.
(indistinct chatter)


118
00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:58.050
- What about sex?
I mean, really. What about sex?


119
00:09:59.170 --> 00:10:00.690
(indistinct chatter)

120
00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:03.290
Well, are you forgetting about the sex?
- What?


121
00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:51.290
- He... he didn't say anything?

122
00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:06.610
(soft piano music)

123
00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:38.050
(indistinct chatter)

124
00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:50.570
- I see that the Zelli girl's husband...
been sentenced.


125
00:12:52.250 --> 00:12:55.490
One year, to be followed
by expulsion from France.


126
00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:10.770
In other words, theft.

127
00:13:11.810 --> 00:13:14.090
- Ah, I feel sorry for her,
all the same.


128
00:13:14.970 --> 00:13:16.930
I can just see how it happened.

129
00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:19.410
People do get hold
of girls like that.


130
00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:21.810
- We should do something
for her.


131
00:13:21.930 --> 00:13:23.530
- Poor little devil.

132
00:13:26.370 --> 00:13:27.930
What did you have in mind?

133
00:13:30.410 --> 00:13:32.050
- We could have her
in the spare room.


134
00:13:32.770 --> 00:13:34.570
She probably hasn't got a bean.

135
00:13:35.330 --> 00:13:37.690
- Huh. But... we don't know
anything about her.


136
00:13:37.810 --> 00:13:39.930
We don't even know
where she's from.


137
00:13:40.050 --> 00:13:43.170
People say she was born
in the West Indies, Martinique,


138
00:13:43.290 --> 00:13:44.930
or some place like that.

139
00:13:45.050 --> 00:13:47.410
- Is that supposed to be good,
or bad?


140
00:13:48.010 --> 00:13:51.650
- I'm not saying it's either.
I'm merely stating a fact.


141
00:13:51.770 --> 00:13:54.730
We don't know anything
about her,


142
00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:56.850
except that her husband
is in jail.


143
00:13:58.090 --> 00:13:59.490
It's true.

144
00:14:01.450 --> 00:14:04.490
- I'm not going to have a discussion
on that sort of level.


145
00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:08.570
- I think you're getting bored
again.


146
00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:12.930
That's the reason you're ready
to bring in anybody at any cost.


147
00:14:13.650 --> 00:14:16.970
- You just want to shut me off and shut me in,
make me into a tame husband.


148
00:14:17.090 --> 00:14:19.970
- As if anyone could do that.
- I won't live like that.


149
00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:24.850
- It's no use doing too much
for people, H...


150
00:14:40.170 --> 00:14:42.330
It's simply no use
doing too much for people.


151
00:14:42.450 --> 00:14:44.050
You know that, H.J.

152
00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:52.210
- All we've ever done for anyone
is to have them in the spare room.


153
00:14:52.330 --> 00:14:54.330
- And look what trouble
they brought with them.


154
00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:56.770
All those types
we tried to be kind to.


155
00:14:56.890 --> 00:15:00.410
- I'm not interested in being kind
to anyone. I'm interested in them.


156
00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:03.010
In character.

157
00:15:05.090 --> 00:15:06.370
In forms of life.

158
00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:09.610
You should've married
a stockbroker


159
00:15:09.770 --> 00:15:11.410
and stayed with him
in South Kensington.


160
00:15:11.530 --> 00:15:13.130
- That is unfair. H.J.

161
00:15:14.490 --> 00:15:17.410
You know perfectly well
I'm only thinking of you. I...


162
00:15:18.970 --> 00:15:23.570
...I don't want us to get into
any more impossible situations.


163
00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:34.170
- Don't you see
how dangerous it is to... to...


164
00:15:34.850 --> 00:15:36.330
close oneself off?

165
00:15:39.890 --> 00:15:42.170
Be afraid of...

166
00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:45.730
Well, just because of some...

167
00:15:47.290 --> 00:15:49.330
...unpleasant experience
in the past?


168
00:16:07.890 --> 00:16:09.490
(birdsong)

169
00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:49.210
It's only a cubbyhole of a place,
but she'll be alright.


170
00:16:56.930 --> 00:16:58.530
(coughing)

171
00:17:13.970 --> 00:17:15.530
(coughing)

172
00:17:41.370 --> 00:17:43.970
(loud background chatter)

173
00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:07.970
- Hello, Mado.
- My poor boy.


174
00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:10.290
What rotten luck.

175
00:18:11.050 --> 00:18:12.290
- Mado, listen.

176
00:18:13.290 --> 00:18:15.170
The worst, th-the very worst,

177
00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:17.330
is that this has happened
when I have no money.


178
00:18:17.930 --> 00:18:20.530
What will you do?
I worry myself to death about you.


179
00:18:20.650 --> 00:18:22.210
- I'll manage something.

180
00:18:25.250 --> 00:18:27.810
Tell me what happened exactly.
I'd rather know.


181
00:18:29.170 --> 00:18:30.770
- It's so stupid.

182
00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:33.290
My defending lawyer
didn't know his métier.


183
00:18:33.410 --> 00:18:35.090
Instead of making a case...

184
00:18:36.970 --> 00:18:38.050
Instead of making a case,

185
00:18:38.170 --> 00:18:40.330
he told the court
how I speak six languages.


186
00:18:42.370 --> 00:18:45.610
Well... no luck.

187
00:18:47.810 --> 00:18:49.730
If only I had some money
for you.


188
00:18:51.170 --> 00:18:54.210
You must write at once to your family
to send you some money.


189
00:18:54.930 --> 00:18:56.530
Have you written yet?
- Yes.


190
00:18:57.290 --> 00:18:59.050
Mm... no.

191
00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:02.250
I'll manage. I'm telling you.
- How?


192
00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:06.850
- I will. Only, I have
such an awful cold, I can't think now.


193
00:19:07.730 --> 00:19:09.250
This noise.

194
00:19:09.370 --> 00:19:10.650
- What will you do?!

195
00:19:11.730 --> 00:19:12.730
- Never mind.

196
00:19:13.770 --> 00:19:14.930
As a matter of fact,

197
00:19:15.050 --> 00:19:17.290
some people asked me
to go and live with them.


198
00:19:17.410 --> 00:19:20.010
- Who? For godsakes, speak up!

199
00:19:20.130 --> 00:19:23.370
- The Heidlers. You don't know them.
They're English.


200
00:19:24.090 --> 00:19:25.770
- It's alright, then.
You go and live with them.


201
00:19:25.890 --> 00:19:27.290
- I don't want to.
- Listen.


202
00:19:27.410 --> 00:19:29.890
Do you want drive me mad?
They'll take care of you.


203
00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:32.410
And I can have
some peace of mind about you.


204
00:19:33.770 --> 00:19:35.570
- My darling, I love you.

205
00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:40.610
You'll be out in spring.
The time will pass quickly.


206
00:19:40.730 --> 00:19:43.610
- Quickly? My God, that's funny.
Quickly.


207
00:19:43.730 --> 00:19:46.090
- I'll come to see you
every week.


208
00:19:48.610 --> 00:19:51.850
And... in spring, we'll go away.

209
00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:53.410
To...

210
00:19:53.530 --> 00:19:55.930
to Berlin or Brussels.

211
00:19:56.050 --> 00:19:59.570
- Promise you'll go and stay
with these people. Promise.


212
00:20:00.410 --> 00:20:03.170
- Yes, yes. Yes.

213
00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:08.650
- Say something.
Quick, speak to me.


214
00:20:08.770 --> 00:20:10.290
- I love you.

215
00:20:12.810 --> 00:20:14.250
I do.

216
00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:18.090
- Alright. And you go and live
with these English people.


217
00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:21.330
Good. Finally.

218
00:20:23.370 --> 00:20:24.930
My poor little Mado.

219
00:20:26.170 --> 00:20:27.530
Are they nice?

220
00:20:27.890 --> 00:20:29.570
- Oh, yes.

221
00:20:29.690 --> 00:20:31.890
Very nice.
(sniffling)


222
00:20:33.010 --> 00:20:34.970
- I won't be able to stand it.

223
00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:26.090
- It's awfully good of you
to worry about me.


224
00:22:26.250 --> 00:22:28.090
- Oh, nonsense. Rubbish.

225
00:22:28.250 --> 00:22:29.810
We're your friends.

226
00:22:30.970 --> 00:22:33.890
- Of course we are.
- I do love your frock.


227
00:22:34.050 --> 00:22:36.330
I shall paint you
with short black gloves on.


228
00:22:36.450 --> 00:22:39.250
Or - no,
she'll have short green gloves.


229
00:22:39.370 --> 00:22:41.090
What do you think, H.J.?

230
00:22:41.890 --> 00:22:43.170
- Do show her the room.

231
00:22:49.970 --> 00:22:51.690
- So here we are.

232
00:22:57.770 --> 00:22:59.970
- You are very kind, you know,
but--


233
00:23:00.090 --> 00:23:02.490
- Oh, if you mean you're afraid
of being a bother,


234
00:23:02.610 --> 00:23:04.330
put that right out of your head.

235
00:23:04.450 --> 00:23:06.250
I'm used to it.

236
00:23:06.370 --> 00:23:09.450
H.J. is always rescuing
some young genius or the other


237
00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:10.850
and installing them in here.

238
00:23:10.970 --> 00:23:13.410
- I really haven't got any money
at all.


239
00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:15.770
I feel I ought to do something
about it.


240
00:23:16.490 --> 00:23:18.370
- Well, what...
what will you do?


241
00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:26.250
- I used to be on the stage,
just sort in the chorus,


242
00:23:26.370 --> 00:23:27.730
in England.

243
00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:31.050
- You must let us
take care of you.


244
00:23:31.170 --> 00:23:32.490
I want it.

245
00:23:33.410 --> 00:23:35.130
H.J. wants it.

246
00:23:37.570 --> 00:23:42.050
I shall be awfully disappointed,
